00:04:06.370 --> 00:04:08.790
So at Google, I wanted to
share a little bit about how

00:04:08.790 --> 00:04:10.620
we structure our team.

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:13.110
We've made a big investment
in content strategy

00:04:13.110 --> 00:04:15.990
as part of our user
experience discipline.

00:04:15.990 --> 00:04:21.209
Content strategy is part of
an overarching group that

00:04:21.209 --> 00:04:23.490
focuses on the user
experience and focuses

00:04:23.490 --> 00:04:26.310
on building holistic
product solutions,

00:04:26.310 --> 00:04:28.980
partnering with a
cross-disciplinary team

00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:32.460
of writers, researchers,
and designers.

00:04:32.460 --> 00:04:34.530
Writers work with
designers to think

00:04:34.530 --> 00:04:36.990
about information
hierarchy on the page

00:04:36.990 --> 00:04:39.270
and to guide user actions.

00:04:39.270 --> 00:04:43.830
Writers work with researchers to
test hypotheses about language

00:04:43.830 --> 00:04:47.460
and inform our insights
with their great research

00:04:47.460 --> 00:04:49.290
capabilities.

00:04:49.290 --> 00:04:52.050
We found that this
holistic approach

00:04:52.050 --> 00:04:57.090
to solving these complex
user product problems really

00:04:57.090 --> 00:05:01.620
helps us create better
user experiences.

00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:03.510
But what might not
be quite as evident

00:05:03.510 --> 00:05:05.610
is the impact that
this focus on language

00:05:05.610 --> 00:05:07.867
can have on the business.

00:05:07.867 --> 00:05:09.450
So I want to share
with you an example

00:05:09.450 --> 00:05:13.470
from Hotel Search on Google.

00:05:13.470 --> 00:05:16.680
This is a great example, where
literally changing two words

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:19.650
had a significant
impact on the business.

00:05:19.650 --> 00:05:22.800
We used to have a label
which read, Book a Room,

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:26.190
and what we found was this was
far too committal at that stage

00:05:26.190 --> 00:05:29.200
in the decision-making process.

00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:32.190
So we switched it to,
Check Availability,

00:05:32.190 --> 00:05:34.830
and what we found was this
was meeting the user where

00:05:34.830 --> 00:05:36.690
they were at in their mindset.

00:05:36.690 --> 00:05:38.679
They were still
considering rooms,

00:05:38.679 --> 00:05:41.220
and they wanted to understand
what dates were available, what

00:05:41.220 --> 00:05:44.490
prices were in that date range.

00:05:44.490 --> 00:05:47.610
And so with those two
words, Check Availability,

00:05:47.610 --> 00:05:51.870
we saw a 17% increase
in engagement.

00:05:51.870 --> 00:05:54.300
That's a significant
impact on the business.

00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:02.000
Sometimes the other end of the
spectrum is harder to measure,

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.460
but equally important--

00:06:04.460 --> 00:06:09.170
that emotional connection that
users have with a product.

00:06:09.170 --> 00:06:13.790
Sometimes we call this emotional
connection brand voice,

00:06:13.790 --> 00:06:15.560
and I want to share a
little bit about how

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:18.470
you might approach defining
brand voice for your app

00:06:18.470 --> 00:06:20.480
or product.

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:23.360
So first, start
with the benefits.

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:27.680
Really consider how to
enunciate the most standout

00:06:27.680 --> 00:06:30.656
traits of your product,
and then consider

00:06:30.656 --> 00:06:32.030
how your product's
differentiated

00:06:32.030 --> 00:06:34.320
from its competitors.

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:37.520
When I had the opportunity to
work on the Google brand voice,

00:06:37.520 --> 00:06:40.640
we took our lead from
the Google search page.

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:45.920
Its simplicity and ease
of use was a cue for us

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:51.250
to inform our brand voice
tenet around usefulness.

00:06:51.250 --> 00:06:55.300
We also took our lead from
the delightful Google Doodle,

00:06:55.300 --> 00:06:59.980
and we have a tenet,
which is around optimism.

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:04.180
And you'll hear more of
this throughout the day.

00:07:04.180 --> 00:07:06.400
So basically, we have
this brand foundation

00:07:06.400 --> 00:07:09.310
with our brand
voice, and it applies

00:07:09.310 --> 00:07:11.170
to our suite of products.

00:07:11.170 --> 00:07:13.330
And I'll share with
you a recent example

00:07:13.330 --> 00:07:16.210
that I had the opportunity to
work on with my team, which

00:07:16.210 --> 00:07:18.250
is the Google Trips app.

00:07:18.250 --> 00:07:19.990
And if you guys
haven't checked it out,

00:07:19.990 --> 00:07:21.910
I highly recommend that you do.

00:07:21.910 --> 00:07:24.160
It's a fun app in
that it helps you

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:26.530
organize all of your
travel information,

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:28.150
so it's available offline.

00:07:28.150 --> 00:07:30.460
So you can download
reservations,

00:07:30.460 --> 00:07:32.920
and if you arrive
somewhere without data,

00:07:32.920 --> 00:07:34.870
you can still access it.

00:07:34.870 --> 00:07:37.150
So when we were thinking
about the benefit,

00:07:37.150 --> 00:07:40.210
we landed on a line,
which reads, "No internet.

00:07:40.210 --> 00:07:41.920
No problem."

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:44.830
Paired with a
delightful illustration,

00:07:44.830 --> 00:07:48.632
we think this really tells
the story of both the benefits

00:07:48.632 --> 00:07:49.840
and the excitement of travel.

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:55.490
So through our experience
here at Google,

00:07:55.490 --> 00:08:00.550
we found that when you have
the foundation of UX writing,

00:08:00.550 --> 00:08:04.060
and you add brand voice, we
know if some of the parts

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:08.060
come together, something
really amazing can happen.

00:08:08.060 --> 00:08:09.760
We believe that UX
writing can certainly

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:12.670
survive with the
fundamentals, but it

00:08:12.670 --> 00:08:15.340
can thrive with brand voice.

00:08:15.340 --> 00:08:16.840
With that, I'm going
to hand it over

00:08:16.840 --> 00:08:20.260
to Allison, who will talk
about our three UX writing

00:08:20.260 --> 00:08:23.016
best practices.

00:08:23.016 --> 00:08:26.848
[APPLAUSE]

00:08:27.810 --> 00:08:29.350
ALLISON RUNG: Thanks, Maggie.

00:08:29.350 --> 00:08:31.630
My name's Allison
rung, and I'm a writer

00:08:31.630 --> 00:08:35.679
on the Trust and Privacy team.

00:08:35.679 --> 00:08:39.940
Part of my job is to explain
why you see ads on Google

00:08:39.940 --> 00:08:42.850
and to show how you can control
those ads to make them better

00:08:42.850 --> 00:08:44.920
for you.

00:08:44.920 --> 00:08:47.110
Like any other
writer at Google, I

00:08:47.110 --> 00:08:48.790
learn a lot of
technical language

00:08:48.790 --> 00:08:50.620
before translating
it into something

00:08:50.620 --> 00:08:53.920
that anybody can understand.

00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:56.110
The technical language
that I start with

00:08:56.110 --> 00:08:59.870
tends to do with
advertising and ad networks,

00:08:59.870 --> 00:09:04.780
but this challenge is common
for any product writing.

00:09:04.780 --> 00:09:07.330
How do you translate what's
happening on your back end

00:09:07.330 --> 00:09:10.690
to the other side of the screen?

00:09:10.690 --> 00:09:12.730
How do you make your
software sound human?

00:09:15.480 --> 00:09:18.540
This work is pretty
intuitive for writers.

00:09:18.540 --> 00:09:21.780
We think about the technical
context we learned about,

00:09:21.780 --> 00:09:23.700
and then we think
about the person who's

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:26.080
using the app or the product.

00:09:26.080 --> 00:09:28.770
And then we decide
what sounds right.

00:09:28.770 --> 00:09:30.180
We tend to say
what we're writing

00:09:30.180 --> 00:09:35.340
out loud to make sure that each
word has the right ring to it.

00:09:35.340 --> 00:09:37.800
But I know many of you don't
have writers on your product

00:09:37.800 --> 00:09:41.790
teams yet, so today I'm going
to try to reverse engineer

00:09:41.790 --> 00:09:44.220
this natural writing
process and guide you

00:09:44.220 --> 00:09:48.510
through three of the
principles that guide it.

00:09:48.510 --> 00:09:51.590
These are principles that
we've kind of internalized,

00:09:51.590 --> 00:09:56.400
and they are clear,
concise, and useful.

00:09:56.400 --> 00:09:57.420
I'll start with clear.

00:10:00.220 --> 00:10:03.870
So let's say that somebody is
trying to sign in to your app,

00:10:03.870 --> 00:10:07.340
and then they mess up their
password for whatever reason.

00:10:07.340 --> 00:10:10.850
And then they see this--

00:10:10.850 --> 00:10:12.530
"Error-- Failure.

00:10:12.530 --> 00:10:15.710
An authentication
error has occurred."

00:10:15.710 --> 00:10:19.145
This sounds terrible, right?

00:10:19.145 --> 00:10:19.645
Right.

00:10:19.645 --> 00:10:22.460
It reminds me of
those restart messages

00:10:22.460 --> 00:10:26.065
we got on our first computers in
like the late '80s, early '90s.

00:10:26.065 --> 00:10:26.690
Remember those?

00:10:26.690 --> 00:10:29.640
There was a bomb that
was about to explode.

00:10:29.640 --> 00:10:32.270
It said something
about system error.

00:10:32.270 --> 00:10:35.520
What was going on there
and what's happening here

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:38.870
is a disaster in software
terms, because the function

00:10:38.870 --> 00:10:40.580
can't be completed.

00:10:40.580 --> 00:10:42.710
But for people,
it's not a big deal,

00:10:42.710 --> 00:10:46.430
and we can tone down
this language a little.

00:10:46.430 --> 00:10:49.640
So in other words,
failure and authentication

00:10:49.640 --> 00:10:52.954
are software problems,
not human problems.

00:10:52.954 --> 00:10:55.370
And we can improve them by
switching them out to something

00:10:55.370 --> 00:11:00.170
that people can relate
to like signing in.

00:11:00.170 --> 00:11:04.280
"Sign-in error-- a sign-in
error has occurred."

00:11:04.280 --> 00:11:09.610
This is better, and notice here
how a single term, sign-in, has

00:11:09.610 --> 00:11:12.230
replaced two different
technical terms, failure

00:11:12.230 --> 00:11:14.000
and authentication.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.990
So that should tell you that
clear doesn't mean precise.

00:11:17.990 --> 00:11:20.360
It means just enough
context to make sense

00:11:20.360 --> 00:11:23.180
to your typical user.

00:11:23.180 --> 00:11:25.730
And I know a lot of you
work on enterprise apps,

00:11:25.730 --> 00:11:28.090
or you're writing
for specialists.

00:11:28.090 --> 00:11:29.750
Specialist language
is totally OK

00:11:29.750 --> 00:11:31.370
when you have a
specialist audience.

00:11:31.370 --> 00:11:35.760
You just have to keep
your own audience in mind.

00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:39.990
All right, so another way you
can make your writing clearer

00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:43.750
is to pay attention to verbs.

00:11:43.750 --> 00:11:45.760
A verb is an action word.

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:49.340
It tends to be the most
powerful part of your sentence,

00:11:49.340 --> 00:11:52.420
and ideally, it will relate
some action to the user.

00:11:55.570 --> 00:11:59.190
Here our verb is, has
occurred, and it's a weak verb,

00:11:59.190 --> 00:12:03.100
because it's describing a state
of being within the software.

00:12:03.100 --> 00:12:05.380
So to make it better,
we'll just switch it

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:09.820
for what the user is
doing, the user's action.

00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:12.056
"You entered an
incorrect password."

00:12:12.056 --> 00:12:12.930
Pretty simple, right?

00:12:16.330 --> 00:12:18.670
OK, so this is clarity.

00:12:18.670 --> 00:12:21.160
With clarity, we
remove technical terms,

00:12:21.160 --> 00:12:24.530
and we put the action in
the context of the user.

00:12:24.530 --> 00:12:25.930
This is an especially
good lesson

00:12:25.930 --> 00:12:28.510
to remember when you're writing
your product announcements

00:12:28.510 --> 00:12:30.760
or your app updates.

00:12:30.760 --> 00:12:33.670
Instead of focusing on the
technical specs of whatever

00:12:33.670 --> 00:12:37.200
new feature you're releasing,
try to focus on the new action

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:38.200
that people can perform.

00:12:41.430 --> 00:12:42.980
The second principle is concise.

00:12:46.700 --> 00:12:49.370
Concise doesn't only mean short.

00:12:49.370 --> 00:12:52.490
It means something
closer to economical,

00:12:52.490 --> 00:12:54.770
so when we're writing
with concision,

00:12:54.770 --> 00:12:56.480
we look at our
message, and we make

00:12:56.480 --> 00:13:00.050
sure that every word on the
screen has a distinct job.

00:13:03.820 --> 00:13:06.490
Here, the header doesn't
have a distinct job.

00:13:06.490 --> 00:13:07.780
We don't need it.

00:13:07.780 --> 00:13:10.210
The body is working
fine without it,

00:13:10.210 --> 00:13:14.470
and this is a very common
problem in product writing.

00:13:14.470 --> 00:13:19.240
We have a ton of superfluous
headers or subtexts or sidebars

00:13:19.240 --> 00:13:22.650
or descriptions, because their
design shows some preexisting

00:13:22.650 --> 00:13:26.969
text field, and then you
feel compelled to fill it in.

00:13:26.969 --> 00:13:28.510
But you should really
avoid that when

00:13:28.510 --> 00:13:33.820
you can, and instead,
practice content first design.

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:35.890
Content first design
will make sure

00:13:35.890 --> 00:13:38.530
that your visuals are
working in service

00:13:38.530 --> 00:13:42.620
of what you're trying to say
and not the other way around.

00:13:42.620 --> 00:13:45.430
So try not to jam your
messages into boxes

00:13:45.430 --> 00:13:47.060
that weren't meant for them.

00:13:47.060 --> 00:13:49.450
And ideally, try
to have designers

00:13:49.450 --> 00:13:51.180
work in parallel with writers.

00:13:55.120 --> 00:13:57.640
OK, so now we've gotten
rid of our header,

00:13:57.640 --> 00:14:00.910
and I've been adamant about
removing extra text here,

00:14:00.910 --> 00:14:03.400
because as you all
know from experience,

00:14:03.400 --> 00:14:06.940
we don't read every
word on screens, do we?

00:14:06.940 --> 00:14:09.400
We scan.

00:14:09.400 --> 00:14:13.660
So this is a mocked up heat map
from an iTracking study showing

00:14:13.660 --> 00:14:17.170
where people's
focal points land.

00:14:17.170 --> 00:14:20.200
We know that people's eyes
follow an F shaped pattern

00:14:20.200 --> 00:14:22.630
as they read screens.

00:14:22.630 --> 00:14:25.540
They read the first line,
maybe the second line,

00:14:25.540 --> 00:14:27.640
but then they start
skipping down the page,

00:14:27.640 --> 00:14:32.550
catching only the first or
second word of each sentence.

00:14:32.550 --> 00:14:36.570
So for this reason, we keep our
text not only concise, but also

00:14:36.570 --> 00:14:37.400
frontloaded.

00:14:39.910 --> 00:14:43.870
Frontloading means to put
your important concepts first,

00:14:43.870 --> 00:14:46.570
so people's eyes catch
those important words

00:14:46.570 --> 00:14:47.620
as they skip down.

00:14:50.580 --> 00:14:54.510
Here, we're in trouble, because
the most important concept,

00:14:54.510 --> 00:14:58.240
the incorrect password,
is all the way at the end.

00:14:58.240 --> 00:15:01.560
And we can fix it by
flipping this around--

00:15:01.560 --> 00:15:03.010
wrong password.

00:15:03.010 --> 00:15:04.842
So now that we've done
this, it turns out

00:15:04.842 --> 00:15:06.300
we don't need
anything else, right?

00:15:06.300 --> 00:15:06.870
This is fine.

00:15:06.870 --> 00:15:08.578
These two words are
working on their own.

00:15:11.240 --> 00:15:14.390
You won't always be able to
reduce your text to just two

00:15:14.390 --> 00:15:17.246
words, but this principle
will always hold true,

00:15:17.246 --> 00:15:18.620
and you can use
it anywhere where

00:15:18.620 --> 00:15:20.480
you're writing for screens.

00:15:20.480 --> 00:15:23.150
Keep the most important
text up front,

00:15:23.150 --> 00:15:28.590
and then ruthlessly edit
whatever comes after it.

00:15:28.590 --> 00:15:29.090
All right.

00:15:29.090 --> 00:15:32.030
Now we're onto our
final principle, useful.

00:15:32.030 --> 00:15:33.610
You want your text
to help people

00:15:33.610 --> 00:15:36.932
to get where they want to go.

00:15:36.932 --> 00:15:39.140
And now we'll talk about
the only part of the message

00:15:39.140 --> 00:15:41.030
we haven't looked at yet--

00:15:41.030 --> 00:15:44.390
the call to action, or CTA.

00:15:44.390 --> 00:15:46.790
Calls to action-- they
tend to be button text,

00:15:46.790 --> 00:15:49.700
or they're hyperlinked,
and they guide people

00:15:49.700 --> 00:15:51.780
to their next step.

00:15:51.780 --> 00:15:53.870
So for that reason,
they need to resonate

00:15:53.870 --> 00:15:55.100
with what they want to do.

00:15:58.290 --> 00:16:02.370
Here, OK is not a good
CTA, because people

00:16:02.370 --> 00:16:06.380
aren't generally happy or
OK with the wrong password.

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:08.970
No, they want to
try again, right?

00:16:08.970 --> 00:16:13.374
So Try Again is a
perfectly good edit.

00:16:13.374 --> 00:16:14.790
But if everyone
here, if you think

00:16:14.790 --> 00:16:17.730
for a minute about all the
hundreds or thousands of times

00:16:17.730 --> 00:16:19.190
you've messed up your password--

00:16:19.190 --> 00:16:22.050
I know for me, it's usually
on airline websites--

00:16:22.050 --> 00:16:25.840
you'll realize this
isn't all we need, right?

00:16:25.840 --> 00:16:26.340
Right.

00:16:26.340 --> 00:16:26.580
Good.

00:16:26.580 --> 00:16:28.170
Yeah, it's early
here in California,

00:16:28.170 --> 00:16:29.650
but I see people nodding.

00:16:29.650 --> 00:16:33.389
Yeah, we need to offer
password recovery, too.

00:16:33.389 --> 00:16:35.430
If you forget your password,
and your only option

00:16:35.430 --> 00:16:39.050
is to try again,
you'll only be annoyed.

00:16:39.050 --> 00:16:40.140
OK.

00:16:40.140 --> 00:16:42.690
So I know you guys
are all pros, and I

00:16:42.690 --> 00:16:45.960
know that you have this basic
sign-in behavior covered.

00:16:45.960 --> 00:16:48.130
It's a very common pattern.

00:16:48.130 --> 00:16:49.680
But what I want
you your take away

00:16:49.680 --> 00:16:53.100
is that paying attention
to writing and the people

00:16:53.100 --> 00:16:57.000
you're writing for can uncover
some of the basic functions

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.340
your app needs to offer.

00:16:59.340 --> 00:17:03.630
So if you don't think of those
edge cases and write to them,

00:17:03.630 --> 00:17:07.720
then you might see some
drop-off in your usage.

00:17:07.720 --> 00:17:12.880
OK, wrapping up, clear,
concise, and useful--

00:17:12.880 --> 00:17:14.940
if you pay attention to
these three principles,

00:17:14.940 --> 00:17:17.640
you'll connect better
with your users.

00:17:17.640 --> 00:17:21.160
But you may have realized as I
walked you through this editing

00:17:21.160 --> 00:17:26.660
exercise that good UX
writing is not a science.

00:17:26.660 --> 00:17:29.450
There's no correct answer.

00:17:29.450 --> 00:17:32.730
These three principles
aren't in perfect harmony.

00:17:32.730 --> 00:17:34.534
There is a kind of
tension in between them.

00:17:34.534 --> 00:17:35.950
They're competing
with each other.

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:43.090
When we made our text clear,
it was still pretty long.

00:17:43.090 --> 00:17:45.700
It wasn't very scannable.

00:17:45.700 --> 00:17:49.410
Then when we made the text
concise, it got shorter,

00:17:49.410 --> 00:17:53.110
but that was at the
expense of some clarity.

00:17:53.110 --> 00:17:56.080
And then finally, when
we made the text useful,

00:17:56.080 --> 00:17:56.890
it stretched out.

00:17:56.890 --> 00:17:57.880
It got longer again.

00:17:57.880 --> 00:17:59.140
It became less scannable.

00:18:01.780 --> 00:18:03.910
So you can find
the right balance

00:18:03.910 --> 00:18:05.800
between these principles.

00:18:05.800 --> 00:18:08.170
When you think about
your user's context,

00:18:08.170 --> 00:18:11.590
think about what she
wants to do in the moment.

00:18:11.590 --> 00:18:14.125
And you can also look toward
your product's brand voice.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.070
Your brand voice
should guide you

00:18:19.070 --> 00:18:23.630
to the right balance between
clear, concise, and useful

00:18:23.630 --> 00:18:28.140
in a way that's true to
your product's character.

00:18:28.140 --> 00:18:31.700
And you can begin to find the
elements of that character

00:18:31.700 --> 00:18:33.950
by thinking about the
core function of what

00:18:33.950 --> 00:18:36.050
your product does,
and then think

00:18:36.050 --> 00:18:38.480
about what makes it special,
how it's differentiated.

00:18:42.150 --> 00:18:45.000
As Maggie mentioned,
Google's brand voice

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:48.840
is designed in part
after our search page.

00:18:48.840 --> 00:18:51.480
Search is an
everyday tool, so we

00:18:51.480 --> 00:18:54.740
like to use everyday,
friendly language.

00:18:54.740 --> 00:18:57.510
And search is also
pretty clever,

00:18:57.510 --> 00:18:59.340
so we use clever
language sometimes,

00:18:59.340 --> 00:19:01.140
but we're not too
clever, because we want

00:19:01.140 --> 00:19:04.740
to be accessible to anyone.

00:19:04.740 --> 00:19:06.930
Our language also
reflects the optimism

00:19:06.930 --> 00:19:09.180
of search that you can
see here in the I'm

00:19:09.180 --> 00:19:12.270
Feeling Lucky button or
those Doodle illustrations

00:19:12.270 --> 00:19:13.751
that Maggie mentioned.

00:19:16.700 --> 00:19:19.280
I like to talk through
Google's brand voice

00:19:19.280 --> 00:19:22.440
with this old slogan
from Google Earth.

00:19:22.440 --> 00:19:23.930
Hello, Earth.

00:19:23.930 --> 00:19:25.940
This is so simple, right?

00:19:25.940 --> 00:19:28.520
This is positive
and forward-looking,

00:19:28.520 --> 00:19:33.920
and it's inclusive to the point
of welcoming the entire globe.

00:19:33.920 --> 00:19:35.750
There's also a
slight play on words

00:19:35.750 --> 00:19:38.780
here, where Earth refers
both to the product

00:19:38.780 --> 00:19:40.230
name and the planet.

00:19:44.600 --> 00:19:48.490
And we all know
this Android slogan.

00:19:48.490 --> 00:19:51.400
This sounds Googly, right?

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:54.580
Be together, not the same.

00:19:54.580 --> 00:19:57.890
Many of us love this,
but why do we love it?

00:19:57.890 --> 00:19:59.410
Why does it sound so Googly?

00:19:59.410 --> 00:20:01.660
How is it working?

00:20:01.660 --> 00:20:04.900
Well, first of all, there
is this overarching theme

00:20:04.900 --> 00:20:09.130
of inclusion that we saw
on the Hello Earth slogan.

00:20:09.130 --> 00:20:11.480
And there's also a
play on words here,

00:20:11.480 --> 00:20:15.310
which reflects the
optimism of our brand.

00:20:15.310 --> 00:20:17.920
Be together, not the same.

00:20:17.920 --> 00:20:21.660
As we read this, there's
kind of cognitive surprise.

00:20:21.660 --> 00:20:25.900
We read, "Be together, not,"
and we expect something

00:20:25.900 --> 00:20:28.570
like the opposite
of together, apart.

00:20:28.570 --> 00:20:32.980
Be together, not apart, right?

00:20:32.980 --> 00:20:37.120
But Google replaces,
apart, with, the same.

00:20:37.120 --> 00:20:39.670
So now we get across the
concept of difference

00:20:39.670 --> 00:20:43.750
and even celebrate it
without any negativity.

00:20:43.750 --> 00:20:45.380
Be together, not the same.

00:20:45.380 --> 00:20:47.230
So again, we're a
very positive brand.

00:20:50.610 --> 00:20:52.350
Coming back to
this drab password

00:20:52.350 --> 00:20:56.580
message, wrong password,
this is great UX writing.

00:20:56.580 --> 00:20:57.240
It's clear.

00:20:57.240 --> 00:20:57.960
It's concise.

00:20:57.960 --> 00:20:58.800
It's useful.

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:01.510
It would work for any product.

00:21:01.510 --> 00:21:04.140
But if this came across the
desk of any of my writing

00:21:04.140 --> 00:21:08.520
colleagues, I think they would
update it to be more on brand,

00:21:08.520 --> 00:21:11.460
and they'd probably change
it to something like,

00:21:11.460 --> 00:21:14.020
"That password
doesn't look right."

00:21:14.020 --> 00:21:16.237
And they would do that,
because since optimism

00:21:16.237 --> 00:21:17.820
is so important to
our brand, we don't

00:21:17.820 --> 00:21:21.870
like to lead with negative
words like, wrong.

00:21:21.870 --> 00:21:25.290
We're also OK with making
the text a little longer,

00:21:25.290 --> 00:21:29.610
a little less concise in order
to be friendly and chatty.

00:21:29.610 --> 00:21:32.800
That password
doesn't look right.

00:21:32.800 --> 00:21:37.860
So now this sounds like Google,
and it's right for Google.

00:21:37.860 --> 00:21:41.140
But that doesn't mean
it's right for your brand.

00:21:41.140 --> 00:21:45.000
So it's up to you to figure
out what the right sound is

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:47.320
for your own brand voice.

00:21:47.320 --> 00:21:48.960
So to help you with
that, you'll hear

00:21:48.960 --> 00:21:51.120
from Juliana, who will
talk about building

00:21:51.120 --> 00:21:53.175
brand voice for a new product.

00:21:53.175 --> 00:21:57.135
