00:24:36.300 --> 00:24:39.150
voice to life.

00:24:39.150 --> 00:24:41.760
Right now, I'm just going
to focus on the writing

00:24:41.760 --> 00:24:44.190
side of things and walk
you through how we've

00:24:44.190 --> 00:24:46.260
started to develop
the Android Pay voice

00:24:46.260 --> 00:24:51.102
and how we bring that to
life through our UX writing.

00:24:51.102 --> 00:24:52.560
The hope is that
this will give you

00:24:52.560 --> 00:24:54.380
all a sense of how
you can start to do

00:24:54.380 --> 00:24:55.505
the same for your products.

00:24:58.780 --> 00:25:03.510
So it's best to start with
a set of brand principles.

00:25:03.510 --> 00:25:06.150
These can be just three
or four adjectives

00:25:06.150 --> 00:25:09.060
that you feel embody your
brand and represent how

00:25:09.060 --> 00:25:12.330
you want people to perceive it.

00:25:12.330 --> 00:25:14.160
A fun brainstorming
exercise you can

00:25:14.160 --> 00:25:16.830
do to help you come up
with these principles is

00:25:16.830 --> 00:25:22.700
to imagine you're signing your
product up for a dating site.

00:25:22.700 --> 00:25:26.390
What words or info would
you put in your product's

00:25:26.390 --> 00:25:28.317
dating profile?

00:25:28.317 --> 00:25:29.900
What is it about
your product that you

00:25:29.900 --> 00:25:34.250
think would stand out or be
most interesting to people?

00:25:34.250 --> 00:25:38.970
What will make them swipe
right and want to learn more?

00:25:38.970 --> 00:25:40.820
You can then distill
these qualities

00:25:40.820 --> 00:25:43.700
into descriptive words,
which will become your brand

00:25:43.700 --> 00:25:46.040
principles.

00:25:46.040 --> 00:25:48.300
We did this exercise
with our team,

00:25:48.300 --> 00:25:51.440
including designers,
researchers, engineers,

00:25:51.440 --> 00:25:54.770
product managers, and marketers,
and we all got together,

00:25:54.770 --> 00:25:56.450
and we did some brainstorming.

00:25:56.450 --> 00:26:00.140
And based on that, as well as
the research that was done,

00:26:00.140 --> 00:26:03.230
we ultimately defined
the Android Pay brand

00:26:03.230 --> 00:26:11.870
as fresh, empathetic,
and approachable.

00:26:11.870 --> 00:26:14.330
Once you have your
brand principles,

00:26:14.330 --> 00:26:16.040
the next step is
to think about what

00:26:16.040 --> 00:26:18.410
these principles will sound
like when you apply them

00:26:18.410 --> 00:26:20.210
to your writing.

00:26:20.210 --> 00:26:23.930
And these will become
your writing guidelines.

00:26:23.930 --> 00:26:27.950
For example, to sound
fresh, we decided

00:26:27.950 --> 00:26:32.540
we need to write in a way
that's snappy and exciting.

00:26:32.540 --> 00:26:34.460
This principle comes
into play a lot

00:26:34.460 --> 00:26:37.490
when we're trying to really
grab a user's attention

00:26:37.490 --> 00:26:39.740
and really hook them.

00:26:39.740 --> 00:26:41.690
And sometimes this can
be before they've even

00:26:41.690 --> 00:26:44.270
started using our app.

00:26:44.270 --> 00:26:48.170
When someone types, Android
Pay, into Google search,

00:26:48.170 --> 00:26:52.310
one of the top results takes
them to our marketing website,

00:26:52.310 --> 00:26:55.190
where they'll see a series
of imagery and headlines

00:26:55.190 --> 00:26:57.410
like this.

00:26:57.410 --> 00:26:59.990
Here, we have a chance
to really pull people

00:26:59.990 --> 00:27:04.310
in and get them to think,
I need to try this app.

00:27:04.310 --> 00:27:06.950
And that's where the
snappy language comes in.

00:27:06.950 --> 00:27:07.951
Headlines like, "Tap.

00:27:07.951 --> 00:27:08.450
Pay.

00:27:08.450 --> 00:27:09.700
Splash," and, "Tap.

00:27:09.700 --> 00:27:10.200
Pay.

00:27:10.200 --> 00:27:13.210
Tasty," not only
highlight the tap

00:27:13.210 --> 00:27:17.240
and pay functionality behind
Android Pay, but also the fun

00:27:17.240 --> 00:27:19.100
things you can buy with it.

00:27:19.100 --> 00:27:22.700
They show that how you pay can
be equally as exciting as what

00:27:22.700 --> 00:27:23.570
you're paying for.

00:27:26.710 --> 00:27:30.180
Empathetic-- we
know that changing

00:27:30.180 --> 00:27:32.280
the way you do an
everyday thing like paying

00:27:32.280 --> 00:27:37.020
can feel uncomfortable and
maybe even a little scary.

00:27:37.020 --> 00:27:40.290
So to counteract that, we
try to write in a way that's

00:27:40.290 --> 00:27:43.710
helpful and reassuring.

00:27:43.710 --> 00:27:47.220
Often, this means anticipating
the questions or concerns

00:27:47.220 --> 00:27:49.449
a user might have
and proactively

00:27:49.449 --> 00:27:50.615
providing them with answers.

00:27:53.980 --> 00:27:58.060
On this screen, we do just that.

00:27:58.060 --> 00:28:02.230
First, by saying, "Enjoy
quick setup with this card,"

00:28:02.230 --> 00:28:03.790
we're reassuring
the user that they

00:28:03.790 --> 00:28:05.410
won't have to go
through that dreaded

00:28:05.410 --> 00:28:10.300
process of typing in a credit
card number on their phone.

00:28:10.300 --> 00:28:11.770
Then we explained
that we've pulled

00:28:11.770 --> 00:28:14.510
in this card from
their Google account.

00:28:14.510 --> 00:28:17.080
That way, they're not left
wondering where in the world

00:28:17.080 --> 00:28:19.669
we got this information.

00:28:19.669 --> 00:28:21.460
Through our language,
we want to show users

00:28:21.460 --> 00:28:23.980
that we're doing
everything we can to help

00:28:23.980 --> 00:28:25.120
make their lives easier.

00:28:28.350 --> 00:28:32.280
Approachable-- this one
means we want everyone

00:28:32.280 --> 00:28:33.960
to feel like they
can use Android Pay,

00:28:33.960 --> 00:28:38.130
that it isn't just for
the most tech savvy.

00:28:38.130 --> 00:28:40.350
To convey that
feeling in our app,

00:28:40.350 --> 00:28:44.370
we write in a way that's
friendly and conversational.

00:28:44.370 --> 00:28:47.730
This means eliminating the
jargon and the formalities

00:28:47.730 --> 00:28:51.120
and simply talking to
users in the same casual,

00:28:51.120 --> 00:28:55.560
easy to understand way
we talk to our friends.

00:28:55.560 --> 00:28:58.290
When we're explaining to
users how Android Pay works,

00:28:58.290 --> 00:29:02.940
for example, we don't
talk about NFC or HCE

00:29:02.940 --> 00:29:05.310
technology, because the
average user would likely

00:29:05.310 --> 00:29:08.370
have no idea what that means.

00:29:08.370 --> 00:29:11.910
Instead, we talk in terms
everyone can understand.

00:29:11.910 --> 00:29:15.205
Unlock your phone, and hold it
to the terminal at checkout.

00:29:15.205 --> 00:29:17.705
We don't need to get into what's
going on behind the scenes.

00:29:21.260 --> 00:29:23.870
That should give you an idea
of how brand principles can

00:29:23.870 --> 00:29:27.080
be applied to writing, and
once you have your own brand

00:29:27.080 --> 00:29:30.074
principles in writing
guidelines in place,

00:29:30.074 --> 00:29:32.240
you should start to have a
pretty good sense of what

00:29:32.240 --> 00:29:35.840
your product's voice
will sound like.

00:29:35.840 --> 00:29:37.840
Then you can take
it a step further

00:29:37.840 --> 00:29:39.590
and think about what
your voice will sound

00:29:39.590 --> 00:29:42.270
like in different contexts.

00:29:42.270 --> 00:29:46.440
This is often
referred to as tone.

00:29:46.440 --> 00:29:49.290
An easy way to remember the
difference between voice

00:29:49.290 --> 00:29:54.990
and tone is to think
about it like a person.

00:29:54.990 --> 00:30:00.270
A person's voice always
stays the same, right?

00:30:00.270 --> 00:30:02.460
But the tone they
talk to you in may

00:30:02.460 --> 00:30:04.770
change depending
on the situation

00:30:04.770 --> 00:30:08.130
or what they're saying.

00:30:08.130 --> 00:30:10.500
In an app, this
might mean talking

00:30:10.500 --> 00:30:14.490
to users in a different way
during a celebratory moment,

00:30:14.490 --> 00:30:19.554
like when they've just
won a prize, versus when

00:30:19.554 --> 00:30:20.970
their network
connection goes out,

00:30:20.970 --> 00:30:24.450
and they're seeing
an error message.

00:30:24.450 --> 00:30:27.360
For Android Pay, we mapped
these different moments

00:30:27.360 --> 00:30:31.230
in the user journey on a tone
spectrum ranging from serious

00:30:31.230 --> 00:30:33.180
to whimsical.

00:30:33.180 --> 00:30:34.710
This helps us make
sure that we're

00:30:34.710 --> 00:30:38.250
using our voice in a consistent
way across the entire user

00:30:38.250 --> 00:30:40.260
experience.

00:30:40.260 --> 00:30:42.660
For your product, the
two ends of the spectrum

00:30:42.660 --> 00:30:45.210
might be labeled differently.

00:30:45.210 --> 00:30:48.210
Your tone might range from
informative to inspiring

00:30:48.210 --> 00:30:51.510
or direct to humorous.

00:30:51.510 --> 00:30:53.100
These are just a
couple examples,

00:30:53.100 --> 00:30:57.120
and you'll be able to tell
what works best for your brand.

00:30:57.120 --> 00:30:59.820
It can also vary a lot depending
on what type of product

00:30:59.820 --> 00:31:03.360
you're building and
who the audience is.

00:31:03.360 --> 00:31:08.100
Once you have the two ends
of your y-axis labeled,

00:31:08.100 --> 00:31:10.650
you then need to determine what
moments in the user journey

00:31:10.650 --> 00:31:13.716
you're going to map.

00:31:13.716 --> 00:31:15.090
A good way to do
this is to think

00:31:15.090 --> 00:31:18.930
about the distinct milestones
or interactions in your user

00:31:18.930 --> 00:31:20.340
experience.

00:31:20.340 --> 00:31:23.190
These can be things like
onboarding, education,

00:31:23.190 --> 00:31:25.950
or troubleshooting.

00:31:25.950 --> 00:31:30.630
To help you decide where these
will fall on the spectrum,

00:31:30.630 --> 00:31:36.310
you can then think about
what the user's goal is,

00:31:36.310 --> 00:31:40.720
what they might be
feeling in that moment,

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:45.790
as well as what you'd
like them to feel.

00:31:45.790 --> 00:31:47.410
To give you an
example, I'll show you

00:31:47.410 --> 00:31:52.220
where we mapped a few of the
Android Pay user touch points.

00:31:52.220 --> 00:31:56.450
The first impression-- when
we're making a first impression

00:31:56.450 --> 00:31:59.084
on the user, we aim for
a very whimsical tone,

00:31:59.084 --> 00:32:00.500
because we're
trying to get people

00:32:00.500 --> 00:32:03.320
excited about Android Pay.

00:32:03.320 --> 00:32:05.720
This could be when they're
seeing an ad, opening

00:32:05.720 --> 00:32:10.307
the app for the first time,
or, as I showed you earlier,

00:32:10.307 --> 00:32:12.140
landing on our marketing
site, where they'll

00:32:12.140 --> 00:32:14.177
be greeted with a
whimsical headline

00:32:14.177 --> 00:32:16.010
and a rainbow sprinkled
donut to go with it.

00:32:19.630 --> 00:32:25.240
When the user is setting up
the app or using it to pay,

00:32:25.240 --> 00:32:28.580
our tone still falls on the
whimsical end of the spectrum,

00:32:28.580 --> 00:32:31.450
but to a lesser degree.

00:32:31.450 --> 00:32:33.230
That's because in
these moments, the user

00:32:33.230 --> 00:32:34.990
is trying to get
something done, so we

00:32:34.990 --> 00:32:36.980
don't want our personality
to get in the way.

00:32:39.740 --> 00:32:44.180
Error messages fall on the more
serious end of the spectrum.

00:32:44.180 --> 00:32:46.970
When a user sees an error,
they might be frustrated,

00:32:46.970 --> 00:32:53.010
so this isn't the right time for
too much personality or humor.

00:32:53.010 --> 00:32:56.280
Needless to say, we're
not going to tell the user

00:32:56.280 --> 00:32:58.230
that something's
up with their card

00:32:58.230 --> 00:33:01.980
or to holler at their bank, if
they're having an issue adding

00:33:01.980 --> 00:33:05.190
their credit card to the app.

00:33:05.190 --> 00:33:07.800
Instead, we want to
be straightforward

00:33:07.800 --> 00:33:11.800
about the issue, and
tell them how to fix it.

00:33:11.800 --> 00:33:14.970
So we'd say, your card
couldn't be added,

00:33:14.970 --> 00:33:16.110
and contact your bank.

00:33:20.530 --> 00:33:23.600
All right, you've
established your voice,

00:33:23.600 --> 00:33:25.610
and you've mapped your tone.

00:33:25.610 --> 00:33:30.290
Now it's time to apply both of
these and do some UX writing.

00:33:30.290 --> 00:33:35.090
It's time to decide what words
will go in your user interface,

00:33:35.090 --> 00:33:38.750
and that ends up being a
combination of everything

00:33:38.750 --> 00:33:41.600
we've told you today.

00:33:41.600 --> 00:33:45.900
To be successful, UI text
needs to be clear, concise,

00:33:45.900 --> 00:33:51.530
and useful, as well as
reflect your brand voice.

00:33:51.530 --> 00:33:53.070
To show you how
you can get there,

00:33:53.070 --> 00:33:55.569
I'll quickly walk you through
what our writing process might

00:33:55.569 --> 00:33:58.027
look like.

00:33:58.027 --> 00:34:00.360
Let's say we're trying to
decide what to say to the user

00:34:00.360 --> 00:34:03.894
the first time they
open Android Pay.

00:34:03.894 --> 00:34:05.310
We can guess that
they're curious,

00:34:05.310 --> 00:34:09.239
so we probably want to tell them
what they can do with the app,

00:34:09.239 --> 00:34:11.850
as well as give them reason
to move beyond this screen

00:34:11.850 --> 00:34:14.940
and set it up.

00:34:14.940 --> 00:34:16.650
At the beginning of
our writing process,

00:34:16.650 --> 00:34:21.469
we might start with something
long and descriptive like this.

00:34:21.469 --> 00:34:24.870
Pay with your phone in stores,
and enjoy quick checkout

00:34:24.870 --> 00:34:27.300
in apps.

00:34:27.300 --> 00:34:31.020
Then we think about the three
principles of good UX writing.

00:34:31.020 --> 00:34:37.350
This text does feel clear and
useful, but it isn't concise.

00:34:37.350 --> 00:34:39.810
So we think about what
pieces of info are essential

00:34:39.810 --> 00:34:41.580
and which ones could
be communicated

00:34:41.580 --> 00:34:44.239
through visuals instead.

00:34:44.239 --> 00:34:47.909
And we might edit it to
something like this--

00:34:47.909 --> 00:34:50.730
"A faster way to pay."

00:34:50.730 --> 00:34:53.460
With this new
version, we've checked

00:34:53.460 --> 00:34:59.340
off clear, concise, and useful,
so we have just one step left.

00:34:59.340 --> 00:35:02.970
We need to think
about voice and tone.

00:35:02.970 --> 00:35:09.210
We'd ask ourselves, does this
text clearly convey our brand?

00:35:09.210 --> 00:35:10.140
Not really.

00:35:10.140 --> 00:35:12.630
It feels pretty generic.

00:35:12.630 --> 00:35:14.250
So going back to our
brand principles,

00:35:14.250 --> 00:35:16.830
we think about how we can
make it feel fresher and more

00:35:16.830 --> 00:35:19.710
exciting, maybe even
whimsical, since this

00:35:19.710 --> 00:35:23.130
might be our first
impression on the user.

00:35:23.130 --> 00:35:25.830
And in our final
iteration, we might end up

00:35:25.830 --> 00:35:28.950
with something like this--

00:35:28.950 --> 00:35:33.120
"Everything you need to
speed through checkout."

00:35:33.120 --> 00:35:35.140
It's a little longer than
the previous version,

00:35:35.140 --> 00:35:38.700
but that can happen when you
add personality to UI text,

00:35:38.700 --> 00:35:41.520
and it's up to you whether
infusing that personality

00:35:41.520 --> 00:35:44.460
is worth the extra words.

00:35:44.460 --> 00:35:48.240
And it isn't always
a clear decision.

00:35:48.240 --> 00:35:51.270
If you're not sure whether more
words will be more effective

00:35:51.270 --> 00:35:56.250
or whether a certain word will
be more effective than another,

00:35:56.250 --> 00:35:58.980
A/B test it.

00:35:58.980 --> 00:36:00.990
From experience, we
can say that when

00:36:00.990 --> 00:36:04.060
you're trying to find the
right words for your product,

00:36:04.060 --> 00:36:08.460
you should never underestimate
the power of A/B testing.

00:36:08.460 --> 00:36:11.010
Through an A/B test we
ran on the Start screen

00:36:11.010 --> 00:36:14.850
in Android Pay, we discovered
that changing the button text

00:36:14.850 --> 00:36:21.900
from "Add Card" to "Get Started"
resulted in a 12% increase

00:36:21.900 --> 00:36:24.060
in click-throughs.

00:36:24.060 --> 00:36:26.640
Pretty amazing.

00:36:26.640 --> 00:36:30.330
A/B testing is a great way to
validate a hypothesis you might

00:36:30.330 --> 00:36:34.390
have or to decide between two
different versions of text,

00:36:34.390 --> 00:36:36.900
if you're just not sure
which one will connect more

00:36:36.900 --> 00:36:39.670
with your users.

00:36:39.670 --> 00:36:41.850
Now I'll hand it back to
Maggie to wrap things up

00:36:41.850 --> 00:36:44.640
and to share a handy checklist
you can start applying

00:36:44.640 --> 00:36:46.085
to your own UX writing.

